            <title>Psychoanalytic Electronic Publishing: PEP Consolidated Psychoanalytic Glossary:
                LIBIDO</title>
            <meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" />
            <div class="dictentrygrp" id="yp0006482592450">
                <p class="dictentrygrp-term">LIBIDO</p>
                <p class="dictentrygrp-dictalso"><img src="images/flag.gif" alt="" />
                    <span class="smallcaps">EN</span>: <span class="dictentrygrp-dictalso-term"
                        >libido</span>; <span class="smallcaps">DE</span>: <span
                        class="dictentrygrp-dictalso-term">Libido</span>; <span class="smallcaps"
                        >FR</span>: <span class="dictentrygrp-dictalso-term">libido</span>; <span
                        class="smallcaps">ES</span>: <span class="dictentrygrp-dictalso-term"
                        >libido</span>; <span class="smallcaps">IT</span>: <span
                        class="dictentrygrp-dictalso-term">libido</span>; <span class="smallcaps"
                        >PO</span>: <span class="dictentrygrp-dictalso-term">libido</span></p>
                <p class="dictentry-term">LIBIDO THEORY</p>
                <p class="dictentry-src"><img src="images/book.gif" alt="" /> Moore, B. and Fine, B.
                    (1990). Psychoanalytic Terms and Concepts</p>
                <p class="dictentry-dictalso"><img src="images/arrow_bw.gif" alt="" />
                    <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001c.yp0005377732370" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">CATHEXIS</span>; <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001c.yp0009492907080" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">CHARACTER</span>; <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001i.yn0014567859780" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">INSTINCTUAL DRIVE</span>; <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001s.yp0011868560200" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">SYMPTOM</span></p>
                <p class="body">Freud used the term <span class="i">libido</span> from the 1890s on,
                    at first loosely, to refer to sexual <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0004718997320" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">desire</span> or sexual appetite. Later he
                    employed the term in a more technical sense as well, in connection with his
                    concept of instinctual drives <span class="peppopup bibtip" data-type="velcro"
                        data-element="zbk.064.0112a.b007" data-maxwidth="300"
                        data-direction="southeast">(1905)</span>. <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">Libido</span> came to designate the idea, central
                    to psychoanalytic theory, that sexual interest or stimulation is continuous
                    throughout life, revealed in a variety of behavioral and mental manifestations
                    related to one another by their common sexual or—to indicate the broader,
                    psychoanalytic sense of that idea—libidinal <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001c.yn0015997845160" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">component</span>. Thus, <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001s.yp0004365369450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">sexuality</span> as an <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001i.yn0014567859780" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">instinctual drive</span> could be called a <span
                        class="i">libidinal drive</span>; a felt or inferred sexual <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001i.yn0003470182460" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">impulse</span> might be a <span class="i"
                        >libidinal impulse</span>; the person or thing that is the target or agent
                    of gratification of such an <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                        data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001i.yn0003470182460"
                        data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">impulse</span> would be
                    called a <span class="i">libidinal object.</span>
                    <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001a.yp0015151865940" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">Affection</span> as well as lust is included in
                    this concept. Affectionate or sexual ties to another person may be designated as
                        <span class="i">libidinal attachments.</span> These usages are intended to
                    indicate the underlying unity of libidinal drives, objects, and attachments.</p>
                <div class="seemore">
                    <a class="seemore" href="#/Document/zbk.069.0001l#yp0006482592450"
