                <p class="dictentry-term">Libido</p>
                <p class="dictentry-src"><img src="images/book.gif" alt="" /> Auchincloss, E. L. and
                    Samberg, E. (2012). Psychoanalytic Terms and Concepts.</p>
                <p class="body"><span class="b"><span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                            data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450"
                            data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">Libido</span></span>,
                    derived from the Latin for “wish” or “<span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0004718997320" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">desire</span>,” is Freud's general term for
                    sexual <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0004718997320" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">desire</span> or sexual appetite, as well as his
                    more specific term for the mental <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yn0009912139530" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">energy</span> of the sexual <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0005442939990" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">drive</span> as distinct from the ideational
                    content of the <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                        data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0005442939990"
                        data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">drive</span>. Freud's
                    propositions regarding the origins, <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001t.yp0007737983140" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">transformations</span>, and effects of <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">libido</span> have been collectively referred to
                    as the <span class="b"><span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                            data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450"
                            data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">libido
                        theory</span>.</span>
                    <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">Libido</span> came to designate the idea that
                    sexual interest or stimulation is continuous throughout life, and that it is a
                    causal factor not only in direct sexual <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0004718997320" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">desire</span> but also in affectionate and social
                    bonds; more generally, <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                        data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450"
                        data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">libido</span> is the causal
                    factor in mental interest in any thought or activity.</p>
