                <p class="dictentry-term">Libido</p>
                <p class="dictentry-src"><img src="images/book.gif" alt="" /> Laplanche, J. and
                    Pontalis, J. B. (1973). The Language of Psycho-Analysis.</p>
                <p class="body"><span class="b"><span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                            data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yn0009912139530"
                            data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">Energy</span>
                        postulated by Freud as underlying the <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                            data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001t.yp0007737983140" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">transformations</span> of the sexual <span
                            class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001i.yn0006585309640" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">instinct</span> with respect to its <span
                            class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001o.yn0004676559070" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">object</span> (<span
                            class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0002322384630" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">displacement</span> of cathexes), with
                        respect to its aim (e.g. <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                            data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001s.yp0020102002960"
                            data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">sublimation</span>),
                        and with respect to the source of sexual <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                            data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yp0012482820020" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">excitation</span> (diversity of the <span
                            class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yp0012210047480" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">erotogenic zones</span>).</span></p>
                <p class="body"><span class="b">For Jung, the notion of <span
                            class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">libido</span> extends to embrace ‘<span
                            class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                            data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yn0009912139530" data-draggable="true"
                            data-direction="southwest">psychical energy</span>’ in general, present
                        in every ‘tendency towards’ or</span>
                    <span class="bi">appetitus.</span></p>
                <div class="seemore">
                    <a class="seemore" href="#/Document/zbk.069.0001l#yp0006482592450"
                        >...excerpted...click to open full glossary entry...</a>
                </div>
                <p class="dictentry-term">LIBIDO</p>
                <p class="dictentry-src"><img src="images/book.gif" alt="" /> Skelton, R. (Ed.).
                    (2006). The Edinburgh International Encyclopaedia of Psychoanalysis.</p>
                <p class="body">Freud's original <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                        data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450"
                        data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">libido theory</span> pitted
                    sexual drives (<span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                        data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450"
                        data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">libido</span>), against the
                        <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yn0007945313930" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">ego drives</span> of self-preservation. Later in
                    his dual <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yn0007283560630" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">drive theory</span>, he contrasted <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">libido</span> with <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001a.yn0013535936150" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">aggression</span> (from the *<span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0020577893270" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">death drive</span>) and he considered that sexual
                    drives and drives of self-preservation were both libidinal. They were together
                    on the side of life, and were opposed by the <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0020577893270" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">death drive</span> which works toward the
                    cessation of life. The <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800"
                        data-type="sticky" data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450"
                        data-draggable="true" data-direction="southwest">libido</span> includes
                    everything that energises and binds people together — ties of loyalty,
                    brotherhood and community — while the <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0020577893270" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">death drive</span> aims for the total reduction
                    of tension, and the destruction of connections. In most cases the <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">libido</span> is fused with the <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001d.yp0020577893270" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">death drive</span>, and the <span
                        class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001a.yn0013535936150" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">aggression</span> of the latter provides some of
                    the muscular <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001e.yn0009912139530" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">energy</span> required for performing sexual and
                    other acts. Freud widened the scope of the <span class="peppopup glosstip"
                        data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001l.yp0006482592450" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">libido</span> to include family ties, friendship,
                    the positive <span class="peppopup glosstip" data-width="800" data-type="sticky"
                        data-docid="zbk.069.0001t.yn0017539537960" data-draggable="true"
                        data-direction="southwest">transference</span> and other affectionate
                    relationships.</p>
                <p class="body">J. A. Ber.</p>
